–1228":"1170–1228","1174–Female":"1174–Deceased","before 1244":"before 1244","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1174":"1174","before 1228":"before 1228","1170":"1170","1280":"1280","1228":"1228","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1235":"1235","1234":"1234","1244":"1244","1200":"1200","before 1240":"before 1240","about 1200":"about 1200","Europe":"Europe","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolkshire, , , England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Clovelly, Devon, England":"Clovelly, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Boson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of North German, Danish, and Norwegian   Boysen  .","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Boie</i> (Old English <i>Boia</i>) + <i>-son</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Boysen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerd, Hans, Erwin, Hermann, Juergen, Lorenz, Siegfried.","North German, Danish, and Norwegian: patronymic from the personal name   Boye  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Boson was born about 1200, his father, William de Boson, was 31 and his mother, Wifw Of John III BOZONN, was 27. He married Mrs. Margery De Boson in 1234, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died before 1244."},"et":{"about 1200–before 1244":"umbes 1200–enne 1244","1200–1244":"1200–1244","–Female":"Surnud","1205–Female":"1205–Surnud","1235–1280":"1235–1280","1240–1285":"1240–1285","1170–1228":"1170–1228","1174–Female":"1174–Surnud","before 1244":"enne 1244","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1174":"1174","before 1228":"enne 1228","1170":"1170","1280":"1280","1228":"1228","1205":"1205","1204":"1204","1235":"1235","1234":"1234","1244":"1244","1200":"1200","before 1240":"enne 1240","about 1200":"umbes 1200","Europe":"Europe","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolkshire, , , England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Clovelly, Devon, England":"Clovelly, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devon, England":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1200–before 1244":"noin 1200–ennen vuotta 1244","1200–1244":"1200–1244","–Female":"Kuollut","1205–Female":"1205–Kuollut","1235–1280":"1235–1280","1240–1285":"1240–1285","1170–1228":"1170–1228","1174–Female":"1174–Kuollut","before 1244":"ennen vuotta 1244","1285":"1285","1240":"1240","1174":"1174","before 1228":"ennen vuotta 1228","1170":"1170","1280":"